This charming little poem describes a picture of the God of Love, and explains the meaning of the symbols under which the god was represented. The subject was a common one for decorative and other purposes; and as it was essential foran ancient artist to adhere rigidly not only to the general type and character, but also to all the details and accessories, of the representation of any recognised mythical personage, we know that we have here an *exact description of a picture perpetually before every Roman’s eyes, and to be found painted on the walls or elsewhere in almost every Roman house.
